aa(lp29
VWoollies are a particularly interesting,
p30
aVquintessential image of the Ice Age.
p31
aVThey were large. They were hairy.
p32
aVThey had large tusks, and we seem to have
p33
aVa very deep connection with them, like we do with elephants.
p34
aVMaybe it's because elephants share
p35
aVmany things in common with us.
p36
aVThey bury their dead. They educate the next of kin.
p37
aVThey have social knits that are very close.
p38
aVOr maybe it's actually because we're bound by deep time,
p39
aVbecause elephants, like us, share their origins in Africa
p40
aVsome seven million years ago,
p41
aVand as habitats changed and environments changed,
p42
aVwe actually, like the elephants, migrated out
p43
aVinto Europe and Asia.
p44
aa(lp45
VSo the first large mammoth that appears on the scene
p46
aVis meridionalis, which was standing four meters tall
p47
aVweighing about 10 tons, and was a woodland-adapted species
p48
aVand spread from Western Europe clear across Central Asia,
p49
aVacross the Bering land bridge
p50
aVand into parts of North America.
p51
aVAnd then, again, as climate changed as it always does,
p52
aVand new habitats opened up,
p53
aVwe had the arrival of a steppe-adapted species
p54
aVcalled trogontherii in Central Asia
p55
aVpushing meridionalis out into Western Europe.
p56
aVAnd the open grassland savannas of North America
p57
aVopened up, leading to the Columbian mammoth,
p58
aVa large, hairless species in North America.
p59
aVAnd it was really only about 500,000 years later
p60
aVthat we had the arrival of the woolly,
p61
aVthe one that we all know and love so much,
p62
aVspreading from an East Beringian point of origin
p63
aVacross Central Asia, again pushing the trogontherii
p64
aVout through Central Europe,
p65
aVand over hundreds of thousands of years
p66
aVmigrating back and forth across the Bering land bridge
p67
aVduring times of glacial peaks
p68
aVand coming into direct contact
p69
aVwith the Columbian relatives living in the south,
p70
aVand there they survive over hundreds of thousands of years
p71
aVduring traumatic climatic shifts.
p72
aVSo there's a highly plastic animal dealing with great transitions
p73
aVin temperature and environment, and doing very, very well.
p74
aVAnd there they survive on the mainland until about 10,000 years ago,
p75
aVand actually, surprisingly, on the small islands off of Siberia
p76
aVand Alaska until about 3,000 years ago.
