aa(lp113
VSo if we were to go deep now within the bones
p114
aVand the teeth that actually survived the fossilization process,
p115
aVthe DNA which was once intact, tightly wrapped
p116
aVaround histone proteins, is now under attack
p117
aVby the bacteria that lived symbiotically with the mammoth
p118
aVfor years during its lifetime.
p119
aVSo those bacteria, along with the environmental bacteria,
p120
aVfree water and oxygen, actually break apart the DNA
p121
aVinto smaller and smaller and smaller DNA fragments,
p122
aVuntil all you have are fragments that range
p123
aVfrom 10 base pairs to, in the best case scenarios,
p124
aVa few hundred base pairs in length.
p125
aVSo most fossils out there in the fossil record
p126
aVare actually completely devoid of all organic signatures.
p127
aVBut a few of them actually have DNA fragments
p128
aVthat survive for thousands,
p129
aVeven a few millions of years in time.
p130
aVAnd using state-of-the-art clean room technology,
p131
aVwe've devised ways that we can actually pull these DNAs
p132
aVaway from all the rest of the gunk in there,
p133
aVand it's not surprising to any of you sitting in the room
p134
aVthat if I take a mammoth bone or a tooth
p135
aVand I extract its DNA that I'll get mammoth DNA,
p136
aVbut I'll also get all the bacteria that once lived with the mammoth,
p137
aVand, more complicated, I'll get all the DNA
p138
aVthat survived in that environment with it,
p139
aVso the bacteria, the fungi, and so on and so forth.
